    <title>Nintendo is making an alarm clock so you can wake up to Zelda and Super Mario sounds</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A photo of Nintendo’s Alarmo alarm clock." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/4AhMmGzoz-5eWsCzABH5xvkukg8=/0x1:3500x2334/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73641941/NSC_Alarmo_6.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Nintendo&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="BgkzMJ"&gt;It’s not &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24051677/nintendo-switch-2-pro-rumors-news"&gt;a successor to the Switch&lt;/a&gt;, but Nintendo does have a new piece of hardware to announce: a motion-controlled alarm clock. The device is called Alarmo, and it “responds to your movements,” which means you can snooze it with a gesture, or stop it by actually getting out of bed. It costs $99.99 and will be available in early 2025, though Nintendo says Switch Online subscribers can &lt;a href="https://www.nintendo.com/us/store/products/nintendo-sound-clock-alarmo-121311/"&gt;purchase it early right now&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="3HfJyF"&gt;It appears this is &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/23/24251736/nintendo-mmwave-device-24ghz-fcc-filing"&gt;the mystery Nintendo gadget&lt;/a&gt; that hit the FCC last month, which revealed that the device features a 2.4GHz Wi-Fi radio and a 24GHz mmWave sensor. In addition to the motion features, a big part of the device appears to be its immersive sounds, which are pulled from five different Switch games: &lt;em&gt;Breath of the Wild&lt;/em&gt;,...&lt;/p&gt;
